	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				My biggest problem w/these events are the absence of a plot and the use of gratuitous violence as fillers. If Verant is after a story line and they want you to participate, why don't they bother to offer a background? Something as simple as offering a short story on the Harpy's Head Tavern for a head's up, or clues into the event would be nice. No, I don't mean spell the plan out. That leaves nothing to the imagination.<BR>
<BR>
It seems there are two sides. Side Y doesn't care for plots or quests. They just want to hurry up and kill things. Side X, the one that thinks events are lame, sees events as a waste. Especially their time. In most cases I agree with the latter. The events aren't interesting at all. It's just a matter of making it out alive or dying. Nil on interaction. (But hey, if they're out to please the majority, let's not forget there are more males playing this game.)<BR>
<BR>
Gordon argues that events bring the heroes out. Most of the events I've seen are catered to the high end of the spectrum. This leaves out the 20-40 level range. I won't buy into the hero argument because no one will convince me that my level 20 rogue is not yet a heroine, and therefore the only option she has is to be a victim. That's why I want to decide whether to participate in an event or not.<BR>
<BR>
There was one such event. I had my 'chanter, a DE level 13, in WC when some NPC DE's started shouting in WC. I left the dervish group and hurried over. Since she's agnostic she got waxed on site. Mad as hell, I brought Esmalyn out. At least she stood a chance against a mid level 20. I /tell a friend and we're on our way, hoping to separate one of the NPC's from the other and show him just how &quot;heretical&quot; my other agnostic was. Before I zoned some level 50's took them out.<BR>
<BR>
Doing away with experience loss would help if you're caught up in the storm. The same goes for experience gain, if your intentions are REALLY role-play. Another suggestion would be to make it impossible for characters that WON'T get experience regardless, because they're too high for the GM NPC, to be unable to do any damage so that those for whom the event is designed (20-40 level range) can have a chance to shine.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
