			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Story and roleplaying is where you find it.<BR>
<BR>
There's no one who says you can't make up your own stories based on what happens.<BR>
<BR>
Some people see an event as a waste of time, a loss of XP, an interruption of whatever it was they were doing.<BR>
<BR>
Other people might, on the other hand, find the story within the action. They might incorporate the events into their characters life and share their tales around a mug of ale at the tavern.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I was there when the foul wyrm Faydedar slogged out of the Lake of Ill Omen. The carnage was terrible. The beast was devouring people whole as it rampaged across the countryside. I tell you, I will never walk lightly around that Lake again after what I saw. Listen...&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And so on. It all depends on what you want. You can either be a passive consumer or take an active approach to roleplaying. Write the story yourself.<BR>
<BR>
Jory
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
