			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Here's the real problem. The events are generally not even in mob level/loot. I've been in numerous Gm events (one epic one, was with a friend as he recieved robe of the underfoot, argueably the best robe in the game) And i can say most of the time the mobs are too high for the typical people in zone to kill, but the loot they drop is not appropriate for the level of people required to slay them. I remeber an event in EK. I was on my way to qeynos to start the Enc FA quest, and as i was going through the zone there were several GM npc's shouting challenges in zone (bandits) All of them were blue to me at 54, but they were probably around 45 judging by how they hit. I then shouted in zone that I would buff bands of people trying to slay the bandits at bridge. So, 25 or so people who were hunting in the zone came to bridge and got level 49 enchanter buffs (i can't cast 50+ buffs on people under 40) Two bandits came the bridge and they got SLAUGHTERED. Obviously the event was designed for higher levels right? So, a high level guild eventually comes, kills the bandits. And surprise, they dropped a evil eye bag and a PRV. To a level 25ish non-twink these items would make me salivate. But to the level 50ish people who got them they are as useful as rusty weapons (well, anybody around 50 probably has one)<BR>
    Here's where the problem is, loot and level of mobs should be adjusted properly, for events for high levels, put them in high level zones (damn, it would be cool to have an event in charasis) or, put them in low population zones to newbie slaughter is to a minimum) Also, don't give level 50 Gm controlled npc's crap like PRV's! Those items belong to lower level events!<BR>
   Another idea would be that the npc's should drop nothing, and GM's should reward roleplayers and valient people at the end of the event by handing out items. This would prevent the ninja looting and *****ing about the items that drop. If the lead GM is around the generate items you could even tailor the items recieved to the class/level of the people recieving items. Imagine this, level 40 skellie appears in Qhills, one low level bard is valiantly leading attacks on him over and over, roleplaying well and generally adding to the event. 5 minutes later all the high levels have tele'd in and run from Nk. Skellie dies, drops no loot. After event GM shows up and awards the bard with an MM drum. Who deserved the item more? obviously the low level.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
